Amazon Polly: Can it handle accented English?¶

Multilingualism in the United States¶

The United States has become increasingly multilingual since its inception as a nation, and even more so in recent years. The United States Census Bureau estimated that around 20.8% of the United States population (approximately 60 million people) reported speaking a language other than English at home (Tamasi, Susan and Lamont Antieau. Language and Linguistc Diversity in the US: An Introduction. Routledge: New York (2015): 192.). As of 2021, that proportion has risen to 21.6% and constitutes over 67 million people. Spanish, Chinese, Tagalog, Vietnamese, French, Korean and German each have over a million speakers in the United States, and there are hundreds of other languages that lay claim to linguistic communities.

Source: Migration Policy (2019 American Cummunity Survey)

Despite the undeniable presence of lingusitic diversity, the United States has remained embarrassingly monolingual. Around 80% of the population speaks only English, and Hawaii (English and Hawaiian) is the only officially bilingual state (Louisiana, Maine and New York are de facto bilingual due to their large numbers of non-English speakers). There is a heavy burden is on English Second Language (ESL) and non-English speakers to learn a new language to get through everyday life in the United States. In fact, the United States has a troubling history of trying to exterminate all non-English speech, and the issues that have stemmed from its monolingual attitude have even bled over into the technology and artificial intelligence (AI) sectors.

Problems With AI and Accented Speech¶

Oftentimes, engineers create speech recognition software with white, English-speaking and Americanized voices in mind, a bias which researchers have only just begun to investigate. A study from March 2020 compared the performances of automated speech recognition (ASR) systems developed by Amazon, Apple, Google, IBM and Microsoft, varying the race of the speaker. Concerningly, all the ASR systems did a significantly poorer job transcribing the speech of Black English speakers than they did for white English speakers – the error rates were nearly twice as large for every ASR system.

Note: WER is the error score, for which lower values indicate higher accuracy.

If racial bias exists even when all the subjects are native English speakers living in the United States, then one can only imagine how ill-equipped ASR software is when it comes to faithfully interpreting foreign-accented English. Given that all the major technology companies tested in the study have headquarters in the United States and boast a large number of both American and foreign employees, improving the accuracy of their ASR systems should be a major priority, especially considering how widespread such software is.

Source: AI Multiple

Our personal interest in examining the difficulties of transcribing accented English accurately stems from Claire's experience as a sports editor at the Emory Wheel. She and her staff writers often have to conduct interviews for articles, both to obtain background research and to get quotes from the article subjects which can be incorporated into the story. Unless the interviewee states otherwise, the Wheel's policy is to record all interviews. The most popular recording tool used among the Wheel's staff is the web-based audio recorder [Otter.ai] (https://otter.ai/), which has the advantage of transcribing the audio during the recording process. Otter.ai also partners with Zoom to transcribe the audio for Zoom calls when participants desire.

While Otter.ai is an extremely helpful tool for journalists who want to avoid listening to hours of interview recordings searching for a couple sentences, it is far from perfect. Claire has often noticed that Otter struggles to punctuate the sentences correctly, often creating long run-ons. It also sometimes fails to transcribe the audio accurately, even when the interviewee speaks SAE. In fact, Claire and her staff writers interview people who speak with both non-standard American English and foreign-accented English, and the transcription accuracy is noticably worse for these interviewees.

During the editing process, Claire has noticed that her writers sometimes directly copy and paste Otter.ai's transcription into the article without editing for grammatical or transcription mistakes, resulting in some inaccurate and sloppy quotes almost making it to print. Journalists have a responsibility to represent the views and speech of their interviewees faithfully, and erroneous transcriptions can clearly inhibit that process. As such, examining the accuracy of Amazon's speech-to-text and text-to-speech services is of particular interest to us, given that it directly impacts Claire's work and potentially that of news outlets worldwide.

Some organizations have spearheaded research that aims to improve ASR systems' interpretation of accented English. Cornell University initiated The Accented English Speech Recognition Challenge in 2020, which provided participants with accented audio samples and called upon participants to provide solutions for better transcriptions. For our project, we hope to use Amazon Polly, Amazon's ASR software, to test Amazon Transcription, Amazon's speech-to-text software, with a variety of foreign-accented English samples and identify areas for improvement and potential racial biases.

Introduction to Amazon Polly¶

Amazon Polly is a machine learning text-to-speech software that falls under the Amazon Web Services (AWS) umbrella. Users provide Amazon Polly with text and choose the text language and the desired voice, and Amazon Polly converts the text into audio. Amazon Polly offers a total of 47 voices, both male and female, across 24 languages – not all voices are available for all every custumization option Amazon Polly has.

One of the most interesting features of Amazon Polly is its ability to read English in a foreign accent. Using the <lang xml:lang="en-US"></lang>, we can make Amazon Polly read the English text with the accent of the chosen language. For example, using the setup pictured below, Amazon Polly will say "Hi my name is Claire and I can say anything that you type" in a French accent.

While the full catalogue of Amazon Polly voices is not available for this type of manipulation, a fairly wide range is. Languages and voices from every continent except Antarctica are available, but for some languages the option to test a male voice disappears. Amazon Polly also gives users the option to create fully bilingual voices and even construct their own accents by creating a phonetic library. However, the accented English feature is as far as the scope of our project hopes to explore.

Project Setup¶

After playing around with the various accented English through which Amazon Polly can speak, we felt confident that if we passed its foreign-accented English through Amazon Transcription, we would receive a high number of errors. Thus, our goal is as follows: to use Amazon Polly to create audio files of different English accents applied to the same sentence, to feed those audio files into Amazon Transcription, to quantify the error for each accent and to compare the results.

We have compiled a sample set of five different accents which we would like to test:

  1. Joanna (English US, en-US)
  2. Emma (English British, en-GB)
  3. Léa (French, fr-FR)
  4. Aditi (Hindi, hi-IN)
  5. Lucia (Castilian Spanish, es-ES)

The above map pins the countries from which the languages we chose originate. We wanted to have a mix of European, Asian and standard English accents to choose from. The Joanna voice is our baseline, and we chose all female voices both to control for gender and due to the limitations of Amazon Polly.

To create our data set of sentences, we used an online random sentence generator to create a data set containing 100 nonsensical and amusing sentences which we will force Amazon Polly to read in the different accents. Each accent will read the same sentences; thus, we can control for potential differences in the input text for Amazon Polly.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
In [ ]:
sentences = pd.read_excel('100Random.xlsx')
sentences.head()

Because one of the main functionalities of speech-to-text services like Amazon Transcription is to save users the time it takes to write and edit manually, we will judge the accuracy of Amazon Transcription on the number of edits required to make its rendering match the original sentence.

One of the most common techniques for measuring the differences between two strings is calculating the Levenshtein distance, the minimum number of character edits necessary to make one piece of text match the other. Thankfully, Python provides the convenient package enchant containing the enchant.utils.levenshtein() function. The function takes two strings as input and automatically computes the Levenshtein distance between them. We will compute the Levenshtein distance for each sentence each accent reads, comparing the results from Amazon Transcription to the original sentence fed into Amazon Polly.

Hypotheses¶

Since we have very little experience with ASR systems and their potential racial biases, our hypotheses as to the results we obtain are not well-founded. However, we can look to others' research to guide our expectations. A 2022 study from DiChristofano et al. found that ASR services generally performed the worst for speakers whose first language was Mandarin Chinese (DiChristofano, Alex et al, "Performance Disparities Between Accents in Automatic Speech Recognition" (2022): 6.) They performed the second-worst for Korean, followed by Spanish, Russian, Portuguese, Arabic, French, German and Dutch.

Although not all of our languages are represented in DiChrisofano's study, it appears as though ASR services have the most difficulty with Asian languages. Thus, we hypothesize that Amazon Transcription will have the most errors for Aditi (Hindi) and Seoyeon (Korean). Based off the above chart, Spanish will be the third-worst, French will be fourth and the British-accented English, since it is the closest to our American English control, will have the fewest errors.

Along with examining which accent produces the worst results, we would also like to see whether particular sentences are especially tricky for Amazon Transcription when read through Amazon Polly. While we can not say with certainty which sounds we believe will be most difficult for each accent to pronounce clearly, we anticipate that sounds specific or more common to American English phonetics, such as the rhotic /r/ sound, will produce larger larger error values. We hope to more clearly define the exact phonetics

In [ ]:
polly = boto3.client('polly', region_name='us-east-1')

voices = ["Joanna", "Emma", "Lea", "Seoyeon", "Lucia", "Aditi"]

For each voice, or accent, in the voices array, we loop through the sentences in our data frame and have Polly synthesize the text into speech. The OutputFormat is specified as mp3, the LanguageCode is American English and the VoiceID is the voice in the array. The .mp3 output gets saved to our directory, which in this case is CHANGE PLEASE BEFORE SUBMISSION, with a separate folder created for each voice. Each file name follows the format 'voiceNameSentenceNumber.mp3' (i.e. Joanna29.mp3). The file gets written as a binary stream and there are casees in place to handle errors if Polly either could not write to the file or the response does not contain audio data.

In [ ]:
for voice in voices:
    i = 0
    for sentence in df["Original"]:
        i += 1
        response = polly.synthesize_speech(Text= sentence, OutputFormat="mp3",
        VoiceId=f"{voice}", LanguageCode = "en-US")

        if "AudioStream" in response:
            with closing(response["AudioStream"]) as stream:      
                output = os.path.join(f"/home/ec2-user/SageMaker/{voice}", f"{voice + str(i)}.mp3")
                try:
                    with open(output, "wb") as file:
                        file.write(stream.read())
                except IOError as error:
                    print(error)
                    sys.exit(-1)
        else:
            print("Could not stream audio")
            sys.exit(-1)

We now have 600 audio files and need a place to store it all. We created an Amazon S3 bucket called speechfilesqtmg3 and we want to move everything there. To accomplish this, we need to loop through every voice in voices, enter the corresponding folder, loop through every audio file within and move them to our new bucket. After creating a String containing the file path, we can use the mv command from the AWS CLI to transfer the variable $string representing the audio file to the S3 bucket.

From Amazon Polly to Amazon Transcription¶

Our next task is to take all the audio files which Amazon Polly generated and convert them back to text using Amazon Transcription, a process which requires us to import a the time, urllib and json libraries.

In [ ]:
import time
import urllib
import json

Just as we did with Amazon Polly, we need to use boto3 to create a transcribe client.

In [ ]:
transcribe_client = boto3.client('transcribe')

We need to create a function called transcribe_file_up that takes the name of the new file, the uri of the input file and the transcribe client as arguments and uploads the audio files to Amazon Transcribe. The input file type is specified as 'mp3' and the language is American English.

In [ ]:
def transcribe_file_up (job_name, file_uri, transcribe_client):
    transcribe_client.start_transcription_job(
        TranscriptionJobName=job_name,
        Media= {'MediaFileUri': file_uri},
        MediaFormat='mp3',
        LanguageCode="en-US" 
    )

The other method we needed was a method called transcribe_file_down for downloading the text that Amazon Transcription created. After performing the transcription and saving it to job, the method checks whether or not the job completed successfully. If the job was completed, then we comb through the response to locate the actual transcription and save it to the text variable. An error is thrown if the job failed; sometimes, the operation requires a few tries before it can be performed successfully, so the method will keep trying a job until the number of tries exceeds 60.

In [ ]:
def transcribe_file_down (job_name, file_uri, transcribe_client):
    max_tries = 0
    while max_tries < 60:
        max_tries+=1
        job = transcribe_client.get_transcription_job(TranscriptionJobName = job_name)
        job_status = job['TranscriptionJob']['TranscriptionJobStatus']
        if job_status == 'FAILED':
            print(f"{job_name} Failed")
        elif job_status == 'COMPLETED':
            response = urllib.request.urlopen(job['TranscriptionJob']['Transcript']['TranscriptFileUri'])
            data = json.loads(response.read())
            text = data['results']['transcripts'][0]['transcript']
            return(text)
        else:
            print(f"Waiting for {job_name}, trying again")
            time.sleep(10)

The final step is to create a data frame containing the original sentences, a language dictionary that holds the voice name as the key and their language as the value and an empty data frame to store our final data configuration.

Our final step was to quantify the error rates among the voices. We decided to use the Levenshtein Distance, a method used to calculate the difference between two strings, as our benchmark.

Source: Wikipedia

We create a Score column in the data frame and apply the Levenshtein Distance formula to the Original and Transcription columns to find the difference between the original randomized sentence and eventual Amazon Transcription output for each of our data points.

Unfortunately, the box plot is a bit difficult to read because the data for French and Castilian Spanish span such a wide range. Seeing such high Levenshtein scores was surprising to us – given how short the input sentences are, a score of 40-50 indicates that nearly the entire sentence was mistranscribed. When we examined the data to look for the sentences that caused such outlier data, we found that the methods by which Polly and Transcribe represent punctuation and numbers skewed our data.

To help clean our data to account for these errors, we decided to strip both the original and transcribed sentences of all punctuation. Additionally, we dropped three especially problematic sentences from our analysis – we expect that removing so few data points from such a large set will not substantially impact the results.

## Statistical Significance

Treating American English as our baseline, we used the differene of means hypothesis test to see whether there is a statistically significant difference between the average American English Levenshtein score and that of a foreign accent.

$H_{0}$: $\mu$$_1$ = $\mu$$_2$

$H_{1}$: $\mu$$_1$ $ \neq$ $\mu$$_2$

z = -/+1.96 with $\alpha$ = .05

Source: stat.yale.edu

First, we calculated the mean Levenshtein score and the standard deviation of the Levenshtein score for each accent and the standard error of the Levenshtein score for American English, all of which are necessary for calcualting the z-score.

In [251]:
eng_mean = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "English"]['Score'].mean()
brit_mean = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "British"]['Score'].mean()
fran_mean = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "French"]['Score'].mean()
hindi_mean = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "Hindi"]['Score'].mean()
span_mean = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "Castilian Spanish"]['Score'].mean()
In [252]:
eng_sd = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "English"]['Score'].std()
brit_sd = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "British"]['Score'].std()
fran_sd = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "French"]['Score'].std()
hindi_sd = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "Hindi"]['Score'].std()
span_sd = clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "Castilian Spanish"]['Score'].std()
In [253]:
import math
In [254]:
# sem_true is standard error
eng_se = eng_sd**2 / len(clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "English"])
brit_se = brit_sd**2 / len(clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "British"])
fran_se = fran_sd**2 / len(clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "French"])
hindi_se = hindi_sd**2 / len(clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "Hindi"])
span_se = span_sd**2 / len(clean_df[clean_df['Language'] == "Castilian Spanish"])

Using American English as the control, we calculated the z-score and consequent p-values for each accent.

In [255]:
def z_score(x, s):
  return (x - eng_mean)/math.sqrt(s + eng_se)
In [256]:
span_zscore = z_score(span_mean, span_se)
brit_zscore = z_score(brit_mean, brit_se)
fran_zscore = z_score(fran_mean, fran_se)
hindi_zscore = z_score(hindi_mean, hindi_se)
In [257]:
import scipy.stats
In [258]:
span_pvalue = scipy.stats.norm.sf(abs(span_zscore))
brit_pvalue = scipy.stats.norm.sf(abs(brit_zscore))
fran_pvalue = scipy.stats.norm.sf(abs(fran_zscore))
hindi_pvalue = scipy.stats.norm.sf(abs(hindi_zscore))

Because our significance level is $\alpha$ = .05, and p-values lower than .05 indicate that there is a statistically significant difference between Transcribe's performance on a given accent and its performance on American English. In other words, a p-value that low strongly suggests that the transcription errors are a result of flawed Amazon machine learning tools and not due to random chance.

In [259]:
plt.plot(['Spanish', 'British', 'French', 'Hindi'], [span_pvalue, brit_pvalue, fran_pvalue, hindi_pvalue], 'o')
plt.xlabel("P-value")
plt.ylabel("Accent")
plt.title("P-values for difference of means (American English) across Accents")
plt.show()

It appears that Hindi is the only accent that showed no statistically significant difference between it and American English – all the others are far below our .05 threshold.

So far, all this is consistent with our hypothesis testing results, but it made us want to examine Transcription's overall performance rather than focusing on each individual accent. Clearly, it can not flawlessly interpret any of the accents – we wanted to see if any sentences gave it particular difficulties across the board.

We first collected all the scores for each sentence and then found the mean Levenshtein score for that sentence, storing the results in a new DataFrame alongside the original version of the sentence which Polly received. The outlier data points appear to come from sentences in which the accent was so unintelligible to Transcribe that it only transcribed a handful of words from the sentence, resulting in an embarrassingly high Levenshtein score. For the mast majority, however, the mistakes were what we would expect: the words were slightly altered in a way that makes it clear that Transcribe had difficulty discerning exactly where one word ended and another began (i.e. French sentence number 66: "Pink horses" vs. "Being courses"). The phonological differences among the accents confused Transcribe, making it impossible for Transcribe to identify sounds which would otherwise be predictable in American English accents. For some reason, these distinctions are far blurrier for French and Castilian Spanish.

Conclusions¶

So, how well does the Amazon Polly to Amazon Transcription pipeline perform? To put it succinctly, not as well as we would have hoped. Although it's difficult to tell whether the majority of the blame falls on Polly's poor pronunciation or Transcription's faulty interpretation, it is clear that the pipeline we have created can not reliably take text to speech and back again. Nine sentences, or around 10% of our data set, had more than five errors in just one sentence, and the sentences which had acceptable scores across all accents were few and far between.

Amazon's services even made mistakes with a standard American English accent, and all the problems which appeared for that voice were exacerbated for the foreign accents. The results of our hypothesis testing were somewhat surprising: we expected that the Hindi accent would produce a statistically significant difference and the British accent would not, but in reality the opposite occurred. The results for Castilian Spanish and French were more aligned with what we anticipated, although the handful of sentences which incurred 40-50 errors are a point of concern as it pertains to data validity.

While our experiment was an interesting preliminary study, there are many areas on which future ones could improve. For one, the sentence data should not include any punctuation, numbers or symbols which could be arbitrarily mistranscribed. Additionally, a wider range of voices should be included to better represent the diversity of English accents present in the United States and other English-speaking countries today. Because we had to drop the Korean accent due to mass data creation errors, we were unable to include East Asian representation. Lastly, the data set should be expanded to include a larger body of sentences, which will reduce random error and increase our confidence in the results.
